            <h2 class="blog-post-title">üß† What Are Cognitive Biases?</h2>
            <p>
              Cognitive biases are predictable mental shortcuts or errors in
              thinking that influence how individuals perceive and judge
              information. Rather than making purely rational decisions, people
              often rely on these mental shortcuts‚Äîshaped by emotion, memory,
              personality traits, and context‚Äîwhich can lead to systematic
              errors in reasoning and behavior
            </p>
            <hr />
            <h4>For example:</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>
                Individuals high in Neuroticism tend to exhibit loss aversion
                and the availability heuristic, as they are more emotionally
                reactive and sensitive to negative outcomes.
              </li>
              <li>
                Those with low Openness are more prone to confirmation bias,
                preferring familiar information and avoiding contradiction.
              </li>
              <li>
                Highly Extraverted and Agreeable individuals are more
                susceptible to groupthink and social conformity, valuing group
                harmony over independent judgment
              </li>
            </ul>
            <blockquote class="blockquote">
              <p>
                üî¨according to Rashidi et al. (2021) and models developed by
                Stanovich, certain people are more vulnerable to specific biases
                based on their trait scores. These associations enable
                personalized interventions to improve reasoning and reduce bias
                susceptibility.
              </p>
            </blockquote>
            <h2 id="example-real">üß™ Real-Life Examples of Cognitive Biases</h2>
            <ol>
              <li>Anchoring Bias:</li>
              <p>
                When buying a car, you see the original price is ‚Çπ10,00,000.
                Even if the seller offers ‚Çπ8,50,000, you think it's a good
                deal‚Äîbecause your brain is "anchored" to the original number.
              </p>
              <li>Loss Aversion:</li>
              <p>
                You decide not to invest in a startup because you‚Äôre more afraid
                of losing money than excited about potential profits.
              </p>
              <li>Confirmation Bias:</li>
              <p>
                If you believe that exercise is better than dieting for weight
                loss, you‚Äôre more likely to read articles that support your view
                and ignore others.
              </p>
              <li>Planning Fallacy:</li>
              <p>
                You believe you can finish a school project in 2 days, even
                though similar tasks previously took a week.
              </p>
              <li>Groupthink:</li>
              <p>
                In a team meeting, everyone agrees to a flawed plan because
                nobody wants to be the one to disagree and disrupt group
                harmony.
              </p>
            </ol>
          </article>

          <article class="blog-post">
            <h2 class="blog-post-title" id="types-bias">
              Types of Cognitive Biases (common types bias)
            </h2>
            <table class="table">
              <thead style="background-color: #f2f2f2">
                <tr>
                  <th>Bias Name</th>
                  <th>What It Is</th>
                  <th>Simple Example</th>
                  <th>Why It Happens</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td>Anchoring Bias</td>
                  <td>
                    Relying too much on the first piece of information you
                    receive.
                  </td>
                  <td>
                    You see a shirt marked ‚Çπ2,000, then on sale for ‚Çπ1,000‚Äîyou
                    think it‚Äôs a great deal even if overpriced.
                  </td>
                  <td>
                    Your brain uses the first number as a reference point.
                  </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Confirmation Bias</td>
                  <td>
                    Paying more attention to information that agrees with your
                    current beliefs.
                  </td>
                  <td>
                    You believe caffeine is healthy, so you only read articles
                    that support that idea.
                  </td>
                  <td>The brain avoids the discomfort of being wrong.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Overconfidence Bias</td>
                  <td>
                    Thinking you‚Äôre more skilled or knowledgeable than you
                    really are.
                  </td>
                  <td>
                    You believe you‚Äôll win a trivia contest without studying‚Äîand
                    lose.
                  </td>
                  <td>People tend to overestimate their abilities.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Availability Heuristic</td>
                  <td>
                    Judging something as more likely because it‚Äôs easy to
                    remember.
                  </td>
                  <td>
                    You hear about plane crashes and think flying is dangerous.
                  </td>
                  <td>
                    Emotional or recent memories feel more important than
                    statistics.
                  </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Loss Aversion</td>
                  <td>
                    Fear of losing something outweighs the pleasure of gaining.
                  </td>
                  <td>You‚Äôd rather not lose ‚Çπ100 than win ‚Çπ100.</td>
                  <td>Loss feels more painful than gain feels good.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Planning Fallacy</td>
                  <td>
                    Underestimating how much time or effort something will take.
                  </td>
                  <td>
                    You think you can finish a project in a day, but it takes a
                    week.
                  </td>
                  <td>
                    Optimism and poor time awareness lead to wrong estimates.
                  </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Fundamental Attribution Error</td>
                  <td>
                    Blaming someone's behavior on personality instead of
                    situation.
                  </td>
                  <td>
                    You think someone is rude for not replying, but they had a
                    bad day.
                  </td>
                  <td>We judge others more harshly than ourselves.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Herding Bias</td>
                  <td>
                    Copying others‚Äô behavior without thinking independently.
                  </td>
                  <td>You invest in a stock because everyone else is.</td>
                  <td>The brain assumes popular choices are smart or safe.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Groupthink</td>
                  <td>Agreeing with a group even when you disagree.</td>
                  <td>
                    You stay quiet in a meeting even though you spot a problem.
                  </td>
                  <td>Social harmony feels safer than standing out.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Disposition Effect</td>
                  <td>
                    Selling assets that have gained and holding losing ones.
                  </td>
                  <td>
                    You sell a stock that's gone up but keep a losing one,
                    hoping it recovers.
                  </td>
                  <td>Emotional attachment drives poor financial decisions.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Hindsight Bias</td>
                  <td>
                    Thinking you ‚Äúknew it all along‚Äù after something happens.
                  </td>
                  <td>
                    After a game, you say, ‚ÄúI knew they‚Äôd win,‚Äù even if you
                    weren‚Äôt sure.
                  </td>
                  <td>Memory becomes distorted to feel more certain.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Illusory Superiority</td>
                  <td>Believing you are better than others.</td>
                  <td>
                    Most drivers think they‚Äôre above average‚Äîstatistically
                    impossible.
                  </td>
                  <td>Boosts self-esteem, but disconnects from reality.</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </article>

          <article class="blog-post" id="matters">
            <h2 class="blog-post-title">üéØ Why It Matters</h2>
            <p>Understanding cognitive biases helps improve:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Self-awareness: Know your own blind spots.</li>
              <li>
                Decision-making: Avoid costly mental errors in work, finance,
                and relationships.
              </li>
              <li>
                System design: Apps and platforms can adapt to individual users‚Äô
                personality-based bias profiles.
              </li>
              <li>
                Mental health: Reduce overthinking, pessimism, and emotional
                reactivity.
              </li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              By using personality-based bias prediction, educators, designers,
              and mental health professionals can personalize tools and
              interventions.
            </p>
